AWS CLOUDFRONT AND S3 STATIC WEBSITE HOSTING

Task Objective

The objective of this task was to understand how Amazon CloudFront can be integrated with Amazon S3 to host a static website securely and efficiently.

Services Used

• Amazon S3  
• Amazon CloudFront  
• HTML  
• AWS Management Console  

Project Workflow

HTML File Creation
        ↓
Upload HTML File to S3 Bucket
        ↓
Disable S3 Static Website Hosting
        ↓
Create CloudFront Distribution
        ↓
Connect S3 Bucket with CloudFront
        ↓
Configure Default Root Object
        ↓
Deploy CloudFront Distribution
        ↓
Open Website through CloudFront URL

STEP 1: HTML File Creation

What I Did:
• Created a simple HTML webpage file.  
• Saved file as index.html.  

Purpose:
The HTML file acts as website content displayed in browser.

Learning:
HTML files are used to create webpage content.

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 2: Uploading HTML File to S3 Bucket

What I Did:
• Opened Amazon S3 service.  
• Created an S3 bucket.  
• Uploaded index.html file into bucket.

Purpose:
Amazon S3 was used to store website files.

Learning:
Amazon S3 acts as cloud storage for hosting files.

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 3: Disabled Static Website Hosting

What I Did:
• Opened S3 bucket properties.  
• Disabled Static Website Hosting.

Purpose:
Website hosting needed to be done through CloudFront instead of direct S3 website endpoint.

Understanding:

Before:

HTML → S3 → Website Endpoint

Now:

HTML → S3 → CloudFront → Website

Learning:
S3 stores website files while CloudFront delivers content securely and faster.

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 4: Created CloudFront Distribution

What I Did:
• Opened Amazon CloudFront.  
• Clicked Create Distribution.  
• Selected Single Website or App.

Purpose:
CloudFront is used for fast and secure content delivery.

Learning:
CloudFront improves website performance and accessibility.

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 5: Connected S3 Bucket with CloudFront

What I Did:
• Selected Amazon S3 as origin.  
• Connected created S3 bucket with CloudFront.

Purpose:
CloudFront fetches website content from S3 bucket.

Learning:
S3 acts as origin while CloudFront serves files to users.

Architecture:

Browser → CloudFront → S3 Bucket

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 6: Configured Secure Bucket Access

What I Did:
• Enabled:

Allow private S3 bucket access to CloudFront

• Kept recommended settings enabled.

Purpose:
To securely allow CloudFront to access S3 bucket files.

Learning:
CloudFront securely accesses S3 without exposing bucket publicly.

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 7: Configured Default Root Object

What I Did:
• Added:

index.html

in Default Root Object.

Purpose:
To automatically load homepage when CloudFront URL opens.

Learning:
index.html works as homepage of website.

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 8: Created Distribution and Deployment

What I Did:
• Created CloudFront distribution.  
• Waited for deployment completion.

Status Verified:

Deployed

Purpose:
CloudFront takes time to distribute content globally.

Learning:
Deployment prepares website for public access.

--------------------------------------------------

STEP 9: Website Verification

What I Did:
• Copied CloudFront Distribution Domain Name.  
• Opened website in browser.

Result:
Website loaded successfully.

Learning:
CloudFront URL acts as public website URL.

--------------------------------------------------

Difference Between S3 Hosting and CloudFront Hosting

S3 Static Website Hosting:
• Browser directly accesses S3 endpoint.  
• Basic hosting.  
• Less secure.  
• Normal performance.

CloudFront Hosting:
• Browser accesses CloudFront first.  
• CloudFront fetches files from S3.  
• Faster and secure content delivery.  
• Better performance through caching and CDN.

Simple Understanding:

S3 = Storage

CloudFront = Delivery

